Running is, for many, naturally difficult. There is stress, anxiety, fatigue, and colds. At some point during the week's treadmill sessions you will need to push yourself extra hard or suffer a lapse in concentration. Allow this to happen, and everything will go pear shaped come run time.
The only way to find positive, disciplined running is to train. You have seen what happens when you start training, and seen exactly where you've been training. You hit off the ground running with gusto and intensity, determined to post convincing and impressive figures on the board, and brush off the rust and discomfort that is a natural -- and learned -- product of training. There is focus. There is repeatable motion. You get a sense of things running together, and when you add volume to push your margins, it begins to feel smooth and inevitable.
You do not have to put in the effort. You've done enough already. Your breakthrough is that you've reached it, that you got somewhere or put time in your feet. The pain doesn't last for that long. If the pain occurs simply in the moment, there is no problem with that, it is merely part of the training. If it leads into other long periods of misfortune, or lead into prolonged suffering, you have some commitments to salvage. It will simply give you the ambition to keep pushing, and rising.
If you can find this focus and motivation, when your moment of nervousness comes and the training will not match what is expected, you accomplish so much more than you would if you did not train. It is not meant for everyone -- the intensity of it alone can devastate some -- but those with lack that additional fuel won't be able to do as well.
